So?  The plaintiff is still getting about 33% of the it and the plaintiff's attorney is getting about 17% it.  If someone just dropped $10 million in your lap for being a total idiot, would you really start complaining that the actual award was $20 million?  I think not, you'd take the money and run, realizing you nearly stole that money as you didn't deserve it.  I don't think either the plaintiff or the attorney should get $0.01 of punitive damages.<br>
<br>
To put it differently, if it's truly "punitive", it should be a fine, and collected for the benefit of everyone.  The current system is sort of like paying your speeding ticket directly to the police officer who arrested you (for his personal use) instead of to a court.  Do you think that would be a good system? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usaurincotg.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Saurin CoTG</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 65<br> <font color=#333399>(2/13/02 12:17:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovefrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=271.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: BSI suing Mythic RE:IRL Auctions - Enjoy Scirocco</span><hr size=1> Tuda I was not trying to argue the issue for or against your point, just supplying some additional information.  However, if I were to argue the point it would go something like this. . . (all in good fun and playing devil's advocate here :-))  I actually think there are some very good sound policy reasons that support your position. <br>
<br>
From a policy/PR perspective this particular case is a bad example to argue as to why the plaintiff/attorney recieve some benefit from the punitive damage award, so I am going to change it up on you for just a second and use the Ford Pinto case.  <br>
<br>
Back in the 70s the Pinto had a dangerous habit of exploding when rearended at even low and moderate speeds.  Why?  Well the design of the car had a metal rod which would puncture the gas tank with moderate body damage causing the explosion.  <br>
<br>
Now in order to prove their case, the plaintiff had to spend a substantial amount of money in costs. (court costs, expert witness fees, testing and so on) Costs in these matters are not recoverable, nor do you get to inform the jury of what they are or how much they are and if you lose or your verdict is not sufficient to cover them, you eat those costs.  In a motor vehicle product liablity claim, those costs can easily be several hundred thousand dollars.  So there can be a significant degree of risk associated with the plaintiff bringing the claim in the first place and thus the benefit accrues to the person that engaged in that risk. (so the argument goes)  <br>
<br>
Now you may not agree with it, and that is fine, many people don't.  The realities are, however, that punitive damage are rarely awarded and even more rarely upheld (there are Constitutional restraints on punitive awards), but when they happen they tend to get a lot of press.  <br>
<br>
